## Boundary Rules (where new docs go)

The structure follows one mechanical rule: **top-level files are universal
singletons (one per service); plural folders hold variable-count items
(zero, one, or many per service)**.

- **`integrations/`** — one file per external system this service talks to
  (cloud provider, message broker, third-party SaaS). Naming: lowercase,
  short (`aws.md`, `kafka.md`, `stripe.md`). Cross-cutting concerns that
  are NOT integrations (logging, security, observability) belong in the
  matching top-level file (`infrastructure.md`, `authentication.md`).

- **`domains/`** — one file per bounded context with real workflow
  complexity. Naming: lowercase, short. Create a new file when a context
  has 3+ states with non-trivial transitions, multiple roles with different
  permissions, load-bearing invariants not obvious from code, or external
  workflow wiring. Don't create one for plain CRUD — extend `database.md`
  instead.

- **`business-context.md`** — exactly one per service. Product framing
  only; no code maps, no schema, no workflow specifics.

- **Every integration doc** ends with a `## Known Divergences (Do Not
  Replicate)` section listing real footguns in the existing code that
  agents must not copy.

